  "text": "LibreOffice Calc formula evaluation follows a well-defined architecture chain. The formula engine begins in the **compiler phase**: `sc/source/core/tool/compiler.cxx` implements the `ScCompiler` class (defined in `sc/inc/compiler.hxx`), which tokenizes and compiles formula strings into bytecode. The compiler parses a formula string like `=SUM(A1:A10)` into an `ScTokenArray` (defined in `sc/inc/tokenarray.hxx`, implemented in `sc/source/core/tool/token.cxx`), which is a sequence of formula tokens.\n\nFormula tokens are defined in `sc/inc/token.hxx` and implemented in `sc/source/core/tool/token.cxx`. These tokens are stored in the `ScFormulaCell` class (defined in `sc/inc/formulacell.hxx`), which represents a single cell containing a formula. The `ScFormulaCell::Interpret()` method (in `formulacell.hxx`) initiates formula evaluation.\n\nThe **interpreter phase** is split across multiple files due to code size: `sc/source/core/tool/interpr1.cxx` through `sc/source/core/tool/interpr6.cxx` implement the `ScInterpreter` class (declared in `sc/source/core/inc/interpre.hxx`). The `ScInterpreter::Interpret()` method executes the token bytecode, evaluating functions, references, and operations.\n\nThe **recalculation scheduling phase** determines which cells need recalculation. The `ScRecalcMode` enum (defined in `include/formula/tokenarray.hxx`) controls recalculation behavior with modes like `ALWAYS`, `ONLOAD_MUST`, and `NORMAL`. The `ScDocument::CalcFormulaTree()` method (implemented in `sc/source/core/data/documen7.cxx`) traverses the formula tree and recalculates dirty cells. The `ScDocument::CalcAll()` method (implemented in `sc/source/core/data/document.cxx`) performs a complete recalculation of all formulas. Recalculation state is tracked in each `ScFormulaCell` via the `bDirty` flag, and the document maintains a formula tree for efficient dependency-based recalculation.\n\nThe complete formula evaluation chain: User enters formula → `ScCompiler` tokenizes → `ScTokenArray` stores bytecode → `ScFormulaCell` holds result → `ScDocument::CalcFormulaTree/CalcAll` schedules recalculation → `ScInterpreter::Interpret` evaluates → Result stored in `ScFormulaCell`."
}

